"1657":"1657","1722":"1722","30 Aug 1657":"30 August 1657","about 1659":"about 1659","about 1649":"about 1649","1642":"1642","1663":"1663","1662":"1662","1595":"1595","1694":"1694","about 1632":"about 1632","1704":"1704","1649":"1649","1638":"1638","1626":"1626","1648":"1648","1659":"1659","Leiden, Zuid-Holland, Netherlands":"Leiden, South Holland, Netherlands","Leiden, Holland, Netherlands":"Leiden, Holland, Netherlands","Leiden, South Holland, Netherlands":"Leiden, South Holland, Netherlands","United States":"United States","New Amsterdam, Colony of New Netherlands (now New York)":"New Amsterdam, New Netherland","New Netherland ( New York)":"New Amsterdam, New Netherland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Kolfs","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Czech (<b>Koliš</b>): from a pet form of the personal name <i>Mikoláš</i>, from Greek <i>Nikolaos</i> (see   Nicholas  ), or a nickname for a very large man, from an altered form of the Biblical personal name <i>Goliáš</i> ‘Goliath’. Compare   Golias  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Nicholas","meanings":["English (southwestern England and south Wales) and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Nicholas</i> (from Latin <i>Nicolaus</i>, from Greek <i>Nikolaos</i>, from <i>nikān</i> ‘to conquer’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’). Forms with <i>-ch-</i> are due to hypercorrection (compare   Anthony  ). The name in various vernacular forms was popular among Christians throughout Europe in the Middle Ages, largely as a result of the fame of a 4th-century Lycian bishop, about whom a large number of legends grew up, and who was venerated in the Orthodox Church as well as the Catholic. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages and also their patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. Croatian and Serbian <b>Nikolić</b> (see   Nikolic  ), Greek <b>Papanikolaou</b> ‘(son of) Nicholas the priest’ and   Nikolopoulos  . Compare   Nickolas  .","History: The colonial official and revolutionary patriot Robert Carter Nicholas was from a prominent VA family on both sides. His father was a British navy surgeon who emigrated <i>c.</i> 1700 from Lancashire, England, to Williamsburg, VA."]}]},{"name":"Jacobus","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the biblical name <i>Yaakov</i>;  see  Jacob ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1356711,"age":16,"year":"1642","julianDay":2320789,"description":"Curacao became a colony of the Netherlands.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1356712,"age":22,"year":"1648","julianDay":2322980,"description":"End of Eighty Years' War with Spain.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Jacobus Kolfs was born in 1626, in Leiden, South Holland, Netherlands as the son of Andreas Kolff. He married Sarah Pietersdochter Hasenbroack on 30 August 1657, in Leiden, South Holland, Netherlands. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died in 1663, in New Amsterdam, New Netherland, at the age of 37, and was buried in United States."},"et":{"1626–1663":"1626–1663","1638–1694":"1638–1694","1649–1704":"1649–1704","1659–1694":"1659–1694","1663–1722":"1663–1722","1595–1657":"1595–1657","30 August 1657":"30. august 1657","1657":"1657","1722":"1722","30 Aug 1657":"30. august 1657","about 1659":"umbes 1659","about 1649":"umbes 1649","1642":"1642","1663":"1663","1662":"1662","1595":"1595","1694":"1694","about 1632":"umbes 1632","1704":"1704","1649":"1649","1638":"1638","1626":"1626","1648":"1648","1659":"1659","Leiden, Zuid-Holland, Netherlands":"Leiden, Zuid-Holland, Madalmaad","Leiden, Holland, Netherlands":"Leiden, Holland, Madalmaad","Leiden, South Holland, Netherlands":"Leiden, Zuid-Holland, Madalmaad","United States":"Ameerika Ühendriigid","New Amsterdam, Colony of New Netherlands (now New York)":"New Amsterdam, Nieuw Nederland","New Netherland ( New York)":"New Amsterdam, Nieuw Nederland"},"fi":{"